metadata.name: Eucalyptus and Sagebrush #35
metadata.description:
Eucalyptus and Sagebrush is inspired by the eucalyptus trees and sagebrush found in California. These plants, and the hills they inhabit, have long been a source of beauty and adventure in my life, and I find myself repeatedly drawn back to them. The sunsets in coastal California are a perfect compliment to these hills, and I set out to represent that combination in this work.

Each iteration of this algorithm feels, to me, like a glimpse out of a car window on a drive up the coast, a pause on a cool morning hike, or a memory of tearing through sharp underbrush with good company.

Stylistically and texturally, I drew from landscapes rendered in oil pastels, placing thousands of tiny circles, alluding to the effect of depositing particles of color onto paper. 

I hope that this work evokes in the viewer the feelings of peace, wildness, and adventure that I feel when I watch the sun set over these hills.

Nat Sarkissian


Notes:
- Append ‚Äú&mag=N‚Äù to the end of the URL in live mode to specify a resolution multiplier. It will render the image N times larger than the size of your window. If you have specified anything greater than 1, a download will start automatically once the rendering is done. The maximum resolution seems to be limited by what your web browser allows. I have been able to output up to 11140px tall and wide using Firefox, which should be enough detail for prints up to 37x37 inches. I recommend keeping the console open while attempting larger renders. It will show you if you have attempted too large a render for your system. N can be any positive whole or decimal number greater than or equal to 1.

metadata.name: Sketch A #47
metadata.description:
Sketch is an open-ended series. Works evolve as I code a generative project, sometimes drastically. Intermediate works usually don't see the light of day - they get archived and forgotten. This series is snapshots of different forms along the way - each standing alone, but also part of a larger meandering work flow. The word Sketch implies incompleteness. This project may end up being two works, or it could evolve for years. Part of the joy of generative art is never knowing what's around the corner. I have no set schedule. There may be multiple Sketches released a week, or it could be weeks or months between drops. I have no idea where Sketch is heading and there is no guarantee of cohesiveness from Sketch to Sketch. Color palettes and forms will change as new ideas are explored.

Sketch A starts very simple. It's the basic grid framework I intend to use for the series. It's just a simple grid with one colored square (usually). Colors are borrowed from Echos/Orbits. Grid size, padding, and line thickness vary.

metadata.name: Flowingcles #108
metadata.description:
"Flowingcles" is a generative art piece that showcases a mesmerizing collection of  circles and abstract shapes. This unique collection invites art enthusiasts to embark on an inspiring visual journey.

Some pieces feature abstract shapes accompanied by a noise effect, reflecting restlessness and energy, while others present a more serene atmosphere with minimalized noise effects. These two approaches offer collectors the freedom to choose the one that resonates with them the most.

The "Flowingcles" collection consists of a total of 128 original pieces. Each artwork has been generated with a unique combination, ensuring individuality and distinctiveness. By incorporating these pieces into their collections, art enthusiasts can adorn their homes, offices, or galleries with a sense of unparalleled art experience and authenticity.

"Flowingcles" stands as a prominent example of modern art, showcasing dynamism, aesthetics, and originality. This collection pushes the boundaries of art and takes viewers on a captivating visual journey. Therefore, me invite art lovers to explore the "Flowingcles" collection and become a part of this visual spectacle:)

metadata.name: GeoRhythms #11
metadata.description:
**"GeoRhythms" is a compound word formed from "Geo," derived from "Geometric" or "Geometry," referring to geometric shapes, and "Rhythms," which means patterns or sequences of movement. In this context, the name "GeoRhythms" might suggest geometric forms found in nature that are combined with a specific rhythm or pattern. This name can represent a fusion of geometry and nature harmonized with a sense of rhythm.
In this project, my endeavor was to present a unique perspective of nature through abstract forms. I hope you all enjoy this project.

metadata.name: Tangentum #104
metadata.description:
We live in a multiverse: an infinite-dimensional space of variants. Everything exists here. Everything is possible. Each subset of a multiverse has its own unique laws of physics, a set of rules, and its own distinct features.

Tangentum creates a projection of a random multiverse subset to a 2-dimensional plane. Each variation is a unique representation of the force field, that exists somewhere at some point in time.

This work starts a series of my visual exploration of functions, continuity, and boundedness, and I would love to share it with you.

metadata.name: 01. morph stripes (revised) #7
metadata.description:
A set of procedurally animated points that define an isosurface is then run through the marching cubes algorithm to generate a polygonal mesh. The shading is a cheap implementation of the spherical environment mapping (matcap) algorithm, using a striped black and white texture.

The result is a hypnotic metaball animation with an op-art vibe.

This is probably one of the first implementations of GPGPU marching cubes that were ever done in WebGL, courtesy of Hector Arellano.

Created in Apr 2014, minted in Nov 2021
by Felix Martinez - @sirokos

Note: Revised version using fxrand(). If you minted the previous iteration and I didn't reach out to you, please get in touch.

metadata.name: Snow Night Generative #4
metadata.description:
Snow night is a particulate artwork for me.
It mix two discipline, 3D art and Generative art, I wanted to give a try with something that I don't really see a lot on FXHash, mixing a 3D world handly created by me and finished by computer, when I say finished by computer is that the computer pick the color (In Six palettes), the snow size and speed for final render of artwork !

I hope you enjoy it !

Made with BabylonJS.

Hash Features :
Six different palettes : 
- Four that have 22.5% chance of being drop
- Monochrome one that have 10% chance of being drop

Radioactivity feature : 5% chances to drop a rare radioactivity features on my artwork !

Two differents snow size : Big and Little
Two differents snow speed : Fast and Slow

Moon Color : Value in RGB

Snow Night by @Disjonquille
Inspired by Jukimoot !

metadata.name: NESTED IDENTITIES #95
metadata.description:
Nested identities redact fingerprints but deeper meaning can still be found.

Nested identifies refers to the idea that a person may have multiple identities that are interconnected and interdependent. These identities may be related to a person's cultural background, ethnicity, nationality, gender, sexual orientation, social class, profession, and other factors. It is possible that a person may want to conceal or redact certain aspects of their identity in order to protect their privacy or to avoid discrimination or persecution. However, even if certain details about a person's identity are hidden or redacted, it may still be possible to infer deeper meaning or understand more about their experiences and perspectives based on the context in which they express themselves and the information that is available.


The concept of nested identities highlights the complexity and multifaceted nature of a person's identity, and how different aspects of identity can intersect and influence each other. It is important to recognize and respect the diversity of identities that people may hold, and to be mindful of the ways in which power dynamics and social context can shape how people present and express their identities. It is also important to recognize that people's identities may evolve and change over time, and that everyone has the right to self-identify and to define their own identity on their own terms.

Press p to download a high quality export.

metadata.name: Kyma #25
metadata.description:
Kyma¬†(/kee-ma/, Œ∫œçŒºŒ±) is a Greek word meaning¬†wave. It is my exploration of an acoustic phenomenon known as ‚ÄòChladni Patterns‚Äô. 

Ernst Florens Friedrich Chladni was a German physicist and musician. He was a pioneer of modern acoustics and made numerous contributions to the field. Chladni's work had a significant influence on the development of modern music theory and the technology of musical instruments. In 1787, Chladni was trying to understand how sound waves propagate and interact with objects. By vibrating a metal plate and sprinkling sand on it, he observed that the sand arranged itself into distinct patterns. These patterns are created due to the interaction between the sound waves and the plate: the sound waves cause the plate to vibrate, which in turn causes the sand to move. The sand will move away from areas of high vibration and towards areas of low vibration. This creates a unique pattern of ridges, circles, and many other shapes.

Kyma continues this study by adding color, light, and composition to the equation. Each iteration is a unique combination of two Chladni plates with different characteristics, accompanied by a palette, background lighting, and variational drawing algorithm. Plates interact with each other, forming patterns from the small detailed net-like grid to megalithic sculptures of unknown creatures and windows to another worlds.

Rendering can be computationally heavy, please be patient and give it some time to draw.
